{"id": 225020548, "title": "Inspectors praise work of staff at Wishaw nursery following recent visit", "text": "Inspectors have praised the work of staff at a Wishaw nursery following a recent visit. Kiddieshack Nursery in the town\u2019s Young Street were given \u2018good\u2019 ratings in all four categories by the Care Inspectorate after the inspection in mid-April. The report states: \u201cChildren were happy, settled and confident in the environment. Interactions between staff and children were warm, kind and nurturing. \u201cStaff were responsive to children\u2019s cues and requests, helping to ensure children felt heard. \u201cEach child had a key worker who was responsible for their care and wellbeing. This caring relationship helped children to settle and feel safe in the setting. \u201cRecent changes had been made to mealtimes with an emphasis on providing more opportunities for children to be independent and develop their skills. This included self-serving food and pouring their own drinks. \u201cChildren were safe and protected from harm with clear policies and procedures in place in relation to child protection. Staff understood the role they played in this and had undertaken training to support them in their role.\u201d Staff were also praised for their work throughout the working day and were described as \u201cconfident, open and professional\u201d. The nursery\u2019s management team were also given a thumbs up by playing a key role in promoting good practice across the facility. The report adds: \u201cStaff felt supported by management team and that their views and suggestions mattered. \u201cStaff meetings were in place, which offered opportunities for staff to share guidance and training, as well as reflecting on day-to-day practice. \u201cStaff were safely recruited, with relevant checks in place before they commenced employment. New staff received an induction, which supported them within their new role.\u201d As well as praise, inspectors also offered certain areas of improvement across the nursery. The report adds: \u201c The service should continue to develop partnership working with parents in all aspects of nursery life. For example, introducing play and stay sessions to support children\u2019s play and learning. \u201cThe management team and staff were reflective and understood that they were on an improvement journey. \u201cAs a result, we were confident that the service were well placed to continue to develop practice with a focus on improving outcomes for children. \u201cCosy spaces had been developed which supported children emotional wellbeing, this included the development of sensory spaces to support children\u2019s curiosity. \u201cWe discussed how the service should continue to develop opportunities to ensure depth, breadth and challenge in children\u2019s learning.\u201d *Don't miss the latest headlines from around Lanarkshire. Sign up to our newsletters here. And did you know Lanarkshire Live had its own app? Download yours for free here.", "summary": "Kiddieshack Nursery in the town\u2019s Young Street were given \u2018good\u2019 ratings in all four categories by the Care Inspectorate after the inspection in mid-April.", "url": "https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/in-your-area/lanarkshire/inspectors-praise-work-staff-wishaw-32914402", "image": "https://i2-prod.dailyrecord.co.uk/incoming/article28920888.ece/ALTERNATES/s1200/0_dmp_wsh_200120nursery_02JPG.jpg", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-05-29 12:59:08", "author": "Ross Thomson", "authors": ["Ross Thomson"], "language": "en", "source_country": "gb", "sentiment": 0.232}